eed to include. It’s possible I should assess whether I need any external services as well. Searching the docs for environment variables might be useful too. It feels like there's a lot to consider here, so I'm trying to keep everything organized. I want to make sure I have everything ready when I'm implementing the request!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_QczhWwzi8CzOlxzn4m5jUS8R|fc_02144fb19cc5966a016a41c863453081908797efbaaba98e34", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sksamuel/hoplite/v3.0.0.RC1/README.md | rg -n \"Environment|System properties|JNDI|Consul|Secrets|AWS|Azure|module|supported|format|props|properties\" -C 2 | head -200", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1380, "output": 124, "cacheRead": 37376, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 38880, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782696031755, "responseId": "resp_02144fb19cc5966a016a41c86061108190aca7919d25650823"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_QczhWwzi8CzOlxzn4m5jUS8R|fc_02144fb19cc5966a016a41c863453081908797efbaaba98e34", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "12-## Features\n13-\n14:- **Multiple formats:** Write your configuration in [several formats](#supported-formats): Yaml, JSON, Toml, Hocon, or\n15:  Java .props files or even mix and match formats in the same system.\n16:- **Property Sources:** Per-system overrides are possible from JVM system properties,\n17:  environment variables, JNDI or a per-user local config file.\n18-- **Batteries included:** Support for many [standard types](#decoders) such as primitives, enums, dates, collection\n19-  types, inline classes, uuids, nullable types, as well as popular Kotlin third party library types such\n--\n26-- **Beautiful errors:** Fail fast at runtime, with [beautiful errors](#beautiful-errors) showing exactly what went wrong and where.\n27-- **Preprocessors:** Support for several [preprocessors](https://github.com/sksamuel/hoplite#preprocessors) that will\n28:  replace placeholders with values resolved from external configs, such as AWS Secrets Manager, Azure KeyVault and so on.\n29-- **Reloadable config:** Trigger config [reloads](#reloadable-config) on a fixed interval or in response to external\n30-  events such as consul value changes.\n--\n44-```\n45-\n46:You will also need to include a module for the [format(s)](#supported-formats) you to use.\n47-\n48-Next define the data classes that are going to contain the config.\n--\n119-\n120-Prefixes can be used to bind selected config to independent data classes. This is useful for modular config loading.\n121:For example, independent modules or plugins load their own config from a common set of configuration sources.\n122-\n123-For example a yaml source containing\n124-\n125-```yaml\n126:module1:\n127-  foo: bar\n128-\n129:module2:\n130-  baz: qux\n131-```\n--\n148-  .configBinder()\n149-\n150:// generally a ConfigBinder will be provided via DI, and these calls will be in their own modules!\n151:val module1Config = configBinder.bindOrThrow<Module1Config>(\"module1\")\n152:val module2Config = configBinder.bindOrThrow<Module2Config>(\"module2\")\n153-```\n154-\n--\n158-A `prefix` can also be provided directly to `loadConfig` and its variants if only one prefix needs to be loaded.\n159-\n160:The `prefix` value does not have to refer only to root properties -- a prefix of `foo.bar` will access config at the `foo.bar` node in the config tree that `ConfigLoader` creates.\n161-\n162-\n163-## Beautiful Errors\n164-\n165:When an error does occur, if you choose to throw an exception, the errors will be formatted in a human-readable way\n166:along with as much location information as possible. No more trying to track down a `NumberFormatException` in a 400\n167-line config file.\n168-\n169:Here is an example of the error formatting for a test file used by the unit tests. Notice that the errors indicate which\n170-file the value was pulled from.\n171-\n--\n196-## Supported Formats\n197-\n198:Hoplite supports config files in several formats. You can mix and match formats if you really want to.\n199:For each format you wish to use, you must include the appropriate hoplite module on your classpath.\n200:The format that hoplite uses to parse a file is determined by the file extension.\n201-\n202-| Format                                                              | Module                                                             | File Extensions     |\n--\n206-| [Toml](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml)                           | [`hoplite-toml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-toml)   | .toml               |\n207-| [Hocon](https://github.com/lightbend/config)                        | [`hoplite-hocon`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-hocon) | .conf               |\n208:| Java Properties files                                               | built-in                                                           | .props, .properties |\n209-\n210:If you wish to add another format you can extend `Parser` and provide an instance of that implementation to\n211-the `ConfigLoaderBuilder` via `addParser`.\n212-\n213-That same function can be used to map non-default file extensions to an existing parser. For example, if you wish to\n214:have your config in files called `application.data` but in yaml format, then you can register .data with the Yaml parser\n215-like this:\n216-\n--\n219-### Note: fatJar/shadowJar\n220-\n221:If attempting to build a \"fat Jar\" while using multiple file type modules, it is essential to use [the shadowJar plugin](https://imperceptiblethoughts.com/shadow/) and to add the directive `mergeServiceFiles()` in the shadowJar Gradle task. [More info](https://imperceptiblethoughts.com/shadow/configuration/merging/#merging-service-descriptor-files)\n222-\n223-## Property Sources\n--\n227-Hoplite supports several built in property source implementations, and you can write your own if required.\n228-\n229:The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource`, `SystemPropertiesPropertySource`, `UserSettingsPropertySource`, and `XdgConfigPropertySource`\n230-sources are automatically registered, with precedence in that order. Other property sources can be passed to the config loader builder\n231-as required.\n--\n233-\n234-\n235:### EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource\n236-\n237:The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` reads config from environment variables.\n238:This property source maps environment variable names to config properties via idiomatic conventions for environment variables.\n239-Env vars are idiomatically UPPERCASE and [contain only](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/basedefs/xbd_chap08.html) letters (`A` to `Z`), digits (`0` to `9`), and the underscore (`_`) character.\n240-\n--\n252-and the prefix is stripped from the env var before processing.\n253-\n254:As of Hoplite 3, the `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` is applied by default and may be used to override other config properties\n255-directly. There is no longer any built-in support for the `config.override.` prefix. However, the optional `prefix` setting can still\n256-be used for the same purpose.\n--\n259-### SystemPropertiesPropertySource\n260-\n261:The `SystemPropertiesPropertySource` provides config through system properties that are prefixed with `config.override.`.\n262-For example, starting your JVM with `-Dconfig.override.database.name` would override a config key of `database.name` residing in a file.\n263-\n--\n265-### UserSettingsPropertySource\n266-\n267:The `UserSettingsPropertySource` provides config through a config file defined at ~/.userconfig.[ext] where ext is one of the [supported formats](#supported-formats).\n268-\n269-\n270-### InputStreamPropertySource\n271-\n272:The `InputStreamPropertySource` provides config from an input stream. This source requires a parameter that indicates what the format is. For example, `InputStreamPropertySource(input, \"yml\")`\n273-\n274-\n--\n556-| `Double`                                |\n557-| `Float`                                 |\n558:| `Enums`                                 | Java and Kotlin enums are both supported. An instance of the defined Enum class will be created with the constant value given in config.                                                                    |\n559-| `BigDecimal`                            | Converts from a String, Long, Int, Double, or Float into a BigDecimal                                                                                                                                       |\n560-| `BigInteger`                            | Converts from a String, Long or Int into a BigInteger.                                                                                                                                                      |\n--\n565-| `LocalDate`                             |\n566-| `LocalTime`                             |\n567:| `Duration`                              | Creates a Java `Duration` from a string in a [duration format](#duration-formats) or from a long in milliseconds.                                                                                           |\n568-| `Instant`                               | Creates an instance of `Instant` from an offset from the unix epoc in milliseconds.                                                                                                                         |\n569:| `Year`                                  | Creates an instance of `Year` from a String in the format `2007`                                                                                                                                            |\n570:| `YearMonth`                             | Creates an instance of `YearMonth` from a String in the format `2007-12`                                                                                                                                    |\n571:| `MonthDay`                              | Creates an instance of `MonthDay` from a String in the format `08-18`                                                                                                                                       |\n572-| `java.util.Date`                        |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n573-| **Kotlin types**                        |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n574:| `Duration`                              | Creates a kotlin `Duration` from a string in a [duration format](#duration-formats) or from a long in milliseconds.                                                                                         |\n575-| `ByteArray`                             | Creates a kotlin `ByteArray` from a string.                                                                                                                                                                 |\n576-| **java.net types**                      |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n--\n602-| `JMXPrincipal`                          | Creates an instance of `JMXPrincipal` for String values                                                                                                                                                     |\n603-| `Principal`                             | Creates an instance of `BasicPrincipal` for String values                                                                                                                                                   |\n604:| **Arrow**                               | Requires `hoplite-arrow` module                                                                                                                                                                             |\n605-| `arrow.data.NonEmptyList<A>`            | Converts arrays into a `NonEmptyList<A>` if the array is non empty. If the array is empty then an error is raised.                                                                                          |\n606-| `arrow.core.Option<A>`                  | A `None` is used for null or undefined values, and present values are converted to a `Some<A>`.                                                                                                             |\n--\n609-| `arrow.core.Tuple4<A,B,C,D>`            | Converts an array of four elements into an instance of `Tuple4<A,B,C,D>`. Will fail if the array does not have exactly four elements.                                                                       |\n610-| `arrow.core.Tuple5<A,B,C,D,E>`          | Converts an array of five elements into an instance of `Tuple5<A,B,C,D,E>`. Will fail if the array does not have exactly five elements.                                                                     |\n611:| **Hikari Connection Pool**              | Requires `hoplite-hikaricp` module                                                                                                                                                                          |\n612:| `HikariDataSource`                      | Converts nested config into a `HikariDataSource`. Any keys nested under the field name will be passed through to the `HikariConfig` object as the datasource is created. Requires `hoplite-hikaricp` module |\n613:| **Hadoop Types**                        | Requires `hoplite-hdfs` module                                                                                                                                                                              |\n614-| `org.apache.hadoop.fs.Path`             | Returns instances of HDFS Path objects                                                                                                                                                                      |\n615:| **CronUtils types**                     | Requires `hoplite-cronutils` module                                                                                                                                                                         |\n616-| `com.cronutils.model.Cron`              | Returns parsed instance of a cron expression                                                                                                                                                                |\n617:| **kotlinx datetime Types**              | Requires `hoplite-datetime` module                                                                                                                                                                          |\n618-| `kotlinx.datetime.LocalDateTime`        |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n619-| `kotlinx.datetime.LocalDate`            |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n620-| `kotlinx.datetime.Instant`              |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n621:| **AWS SDK types**                       | Requires `hoplite-aws` module                                                                                                                                                                               |\n622-| `com.amazonaws.regions.Region`          |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n623:| **Micrometer types**                    | Requires `hoplite-micrometer-xxx` modules                                                                                                                                                                   |\n624-| `io.micrometer.statsd.DatadogConfig`    | Converts a nested object to an instance of DatadogConfig                                                                                                                                                    |\n625-| `io.micrometer.statsd.PrometheusConfig` | Converts a nested object to an instance of PrometheusConfig                                                                                                                                                 |\n--\n631-\n632-\n633:## Duration formats\n634-\n635:Duration types support unit strings in the following format (lower case only), with an optional space between the unit value and the unit type.\n636-\n637-* `ns`, `nano`, `nanos`, `nanosecond`, `nanoseconds`\n--\n697-### Optional Preprocessors\n698-\n699:These preprocessors must be added to the `ConfigBuilder` before they take effect, and require extra modules to be added to the build.\n700-\n701-| Preprocessor                    | Function                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n702-|:--------------------------------|:-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n703:| `AwsSecretsManagerPreprocessor` | Replaces strings of the form awssm://key by looking up the value of 'key' from [AWS Secrets Manager](https://aws.amazon.com/secrets-manager/).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-aws` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                              |\n704:| `AzureKeyVaultPreprocessor`     | Replaces strings of the form azurekeyvault://key by looking up the value of 'key' from [Azure Key Vault](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/key-vault/).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-azure` module to be added to the classpath.                                                              |\n705:| `ParameterStorePreprocessor`    | Replaces strings of the form ${ssm:key} by looking up the value of 'key' from the [AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-parameter-store.html).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-aws` module to be added to the classpath. |\n706:| `ConsulConfigPreprocessor`      | Replaces strings of the form consul://key by looking up the value of 'key' from a [Consul](https://www.consul.io/) server.<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-consul` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                                               |\n707:| `VaultSecretPreprocessor`       | Replaces strings of the form vault://key by looking up the value of 'key' from a [Vault](https://www.vaultproject.io/) instance.<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-vault` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                                          |\n708:| `GcpSecretManagerPreprocessor`  | Replaces strings of the form `gcpsm://projects/{projectId}/secrets/{secretName}/versions/{version:latest}` by looking up the value from a [Google Cloud Secret Manager](https://cloud.google.com/secret-manager) instance.<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-gcp` module to be added to the classpath.  |\n709-\n710-\n--\n738-\n739-It is quite common to output the resolved config at startup for reference when debugging. In this case, the default `toString` generated by Kotlin's data classes is very useful.\n740:However configuration typically includes sensitive information such as passwords or keys which normally you would not want to appear in logs.\n741-\n742-To avoid sensitive fields appearing in the log output, Hoplite provides a built in type called `Masked` which is a wrapper around a String.\n--\n762-If you marshall your config to a String using a reflection based tool like Jackson, it will still be able to see the underlying value.\n763-In these cases, you would need to register a custom serializer.\n764:For the Jackson project, a `HopliteModule` object is available in the `hoplite-json` module.\n765-Register this with your Jackson mapper, like `mapper.registerModule(HopliteModule)` and then `Masked` values will be ouputted into Json as \"****\"\n766-\n--\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782696035679}]}
